<!-- <title>Previo a la unidad</title> -->
<title>Exploración</title>
<!-- <title component="metadata">Alineado con <xref ref="graVV-uniYY-secZZ" text="title"/></title> -->
<!-- <title component="metadata">Alineado con <xref ref="lec-VVVVVV" text="title"/></title> -->

<statement>
  <p>Si sigues doblando tiras de fracciones, ¿en cuántas partes las puedes doblar? ¿Puedes doblarlas en 100 partes iguales?</p>
</statement>

<solution>
  <p>[++++++++++++++++++++]</p>
  <p>Sample response. If I keep folding in half, I get 2 parts, then 4, then 8, then 16, 32, and 64. We did 2, 4, and 8 with fraction strips. If I fold into 3 equal pieces I get 3, then 9, then 27, then 81. I could also alternate folding into 2 equal pieces and 3 equal pieces like we did to gets sixths. I could get 12 parts or 18 parts if I fold again into 2 or 3 equal pieces. And then 24, 36, or 54 parts if I fold again. I don't think I can get 100 unless I do a more complicated fold.</p>
</solution>

</exercise>
